      <hedline>
        <hl1>Now What? A TV Special Issue</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Frances E Scanlon letter on Sept 20 Magazine issue about television</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Awash in the baptism of born-again punditry, Chris Matthews's ''Hardball'' is a cable-televised crusade. Though James Traub's ''Inyourface the Nation'' suggests that ''if you want depth, you can read a book,'' why bother when nightly you can spin past the land mines of rhetoric to salvation via Matthews's ministry?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Awash in the baptism of born-again punditry, Chris Matthews's ''Hardball'' is a cable-televised crusade. Though James Traub's ''Inyourface the Nation'' suggests that ''if you want depth, you can read a book,'' why bother when nightly you can spin past the land mines of rhetoric to salvation via Matthews's ministry?</p>
        <p>Surely there isn't a healer afoot today in the fields of tent revivalism who couldn't learn a thing or two from Preacher Matthews.</p>
        <p>Frances E. Scanlon  Flushing, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
